    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="351"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d351">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">818.00/287½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">29 December, 1917</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: What do you think about
                        this?<note n="5" xml:id="d351fn1">Projected revolution of Alfredo Volio; see
                            <ref target="frus1917#pg_348">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1917, p. 348</ref>.</note> To
                    have anything at all to do with it is certainly to play with fire and to risk
                    incurring the suspicion of every state in Latin America; and yet, if the man is
                    sincere, what he purposes (always provided his programme does in all good faith
                    include a free and constitutional election) must of necessity claim our
                    sympathy.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
